a Binary encoding: 1 = Yes/Present/Hybrid/Transplanted, 0 = No/Absent/Inbred/Direct seeded.
The feature set encompassed eight pre-planting variables (X_1-X_8) related to land preparation, establishment decisions, and irrigation access; nine nutrient management variables (X_9-X_17) capturing fertilization practices; nine pest and disease variables (X_18-X_26) documenting challenges and management responses; and one environmental variable (X_27) accounting for weather-related challenges during the season.
This format directly reflected the activity-based categorization framework documented in the qualitative and quantitative findings. Pre-planting features (X_1-X_8) operationalized the universal transplanting practice (100% of farmers, Table 6, Theme I1), variety preferences (83% hybrid, Table 9), seed rate variation (median 18 kg, IQR 15-30 kg, Table 9), land preparation methods (98% tractor use, 65% rotavator, Table 9), and irrigation availability (100% NIA access, Table 9) identified during Phase 1 investigations.
Nutrient management features (X_9-X_17) operationalized the multi-stage fertilization patterns documented in 100% farmer interviews (Table 6, Theme I9) and quantitative surveys (Table 7, Table 9). Rather than recording raw fertilizer product quantities (which varied across five common formulations: Urea 46-0-0, Ammonium Sulfate 21-0-0, Ammonium Phosphate 16-20-0, Complete 14-14-14, Potash 0-0-60 documented in Table 7), features X_9-X_17 represent standardized NPK nutrient content computed as detailed in Equations [7]-[9]. This standardization addressed the wide variation in fertilizer products and timing documented in Table 9 while enabling model training on nutrient-equivalent units aligned with agronomic principles (DA-ATI CAR, 2022).
Pest and disease features (X_18-X_22) captured the five key challenges identified through thematic analysis: stem borer (89% prevalence, Table 9), golden apple snail/kuhol (63%), rats (13%), cutworms (6%), and rice blast (19%). These binary presence indicators reflected the preventive IPM orientation documented in qualitative findings (Table 6, Theme I4: 10/11 reported limited routine insecticide use) rather than severity gradations, as farmers consistently described pest management in present/absent rather than quantitative severity terms. 
Pest management input features (X_23-X_26) quantified protection product usage: insecticide (median 0 L), herbicide (median 0.5 L), rat poison (median 0 g), and molluscicide (median 0 sachets), aligning with the concentrated application windows around establishment documented in both qualitative interviews and quantitative patterns (Table 9).
The environmental challenge variable (X_27) operationalized the weather-related constraints reported by 80% of farmers (Table 9), including flooding near transplanting and dry-season water stress documented in Table 8. Unlike other input features that represent farmer-controlled management decisions, X_27 reflects an external stochastic factor. It was retained in the feature set because it captures whether a season experienced serious adverse weather, which is known to have large effects on yield in the study area.
The complete 27-feature specification established the input variable framework for subsequent model development, with each feature directly traceable to empirical observations from farmer interviews and surveys. This traceability ensured that the predictive model would accept inputs aligned with actual farming practices and decision-making contexts documented during requirements planning, supporting the development of a decision-support tool grounded in local agricultural realities rather than theoretical or externally-imposed variable selections.
Model Development and Hyperparameter Optimization
Following the feature set specification derived from Phase 1, the model development phase focused on training, optimizing, and validating a Random Forest Regressor for palay yield prediction using the 27 input features (X_1-X_27) and the target variable Y (palay yield in kilograms). This section presents the hyperparameter search process, the optimal model configuration, and performance evaluation on the held-out test set.
Hyperparameter search and optimal configuration
The hyperparameter optimization process evaluated 216 Random Forest configurations through 3-fold cross-validation on the training set (presented in Table 5). A total of 54 farms were included in the analysis, yielding 37 training samples (70%) and 17 test samples (30%) following the 70-30 split procedure detailed in the methodology. Table 13 presents the optimal hyperparameter configuration that achieved the highest cross-validation performance among all evaluated combinations. 
The optimal configuration balanced model complexity (200 trees with maximum depth 10) against overfitting risk (controlled through max_depth constraint and feature subsampling via max_features=‘sqrt’). The max_depth=10 constraint prevented individual trees from growing excessively deep and memorizing training data, while the ‘sqrt’ feature selection ensured each split considered approximately 5 randomly selected features from the full set of 27, promoting diversity among the 200 trees in the ensemble (James et al., 2023b). The grid search identified this configuration as achieving the highest mean cross-validation R^2 of 0.6040 ± 0.1043 across the three folds, indicating consistent performance across different training/validation splits within the 70% training set. Complete evaluation results for all hyperparameter combinations are provided in Appendix Table 6 for transparency and reproducibility.
Table 13. Optimal Random Forest hyperparameters identified through grid search.
Hyperparameter	Selected Value	Interpretation
n_estimators	200	200 decision trees in the ensemble
max_depth	10	Maximum tree depth of 10 levels
min_samples_split	2	Minimum 2 samples required to split a node
min_samples_leaf	1	Minimum 1 sample required at a leaf node 
max_features	'sqrt'	√27  ≈ 5 features considered at each split 
Test set performance
The optimized Random Forest model, trained on 37 farms, was evaluated on a held-out test set of 17 farms (30% of the dataset) that were not used during training or hyperparameter optimization. Table 14 presents the performance metrics on this independent test set.
The test set R^2 of 0.765 indicates that the model explains approximately 76.5% of yield variance in previously unseen farms. The unexplained 23.5% likely reflects unmeasured variables excluded during Phase 1 due to data availability constraints, including quantitative weather data (rainfall amounts, temperature extremes), soil quality differences, and management execution quality. This performance aligns with related agricultural studies using ensemble methods on small datasets (David, 2023: R^2=0.78; Jiya et al., 2023: R^2=0.72).
The RMSE of 2,286 kg corresponds to approximately 36% of the median yield (6,287 kg, Table 9), reflecting the substantial variability documented in Phase 1 (yield range 1,220-20,790 kg driven by farm size heterogeneity, seed quality variation, fertilizer rate differences, and weather challenges affecting 80% of farmers). The MAE of 1,731 kg, being lower than RMSE, indicates that while typical errors are moderate, occasional larger errors occur at the distribution's extremes. 
Table 14. Performance metrics of the optimized Random Forest model on the hold-out test set (n=17 farms).
Metric	Value
R^2 (coefficient of determination)	0.765
RMSE (root mean squared error)	2,286 kg
MAE (mean absolute error)	1,731 kg
MSE (mean squared error)	5,225,856 kg²

 
Fig. 20. Predicted versus actual yield for training (blue) and test (orange) sets. The dashed line represents perfect 1:1 agreement. Test samples maintain reasonable alignment despite not being used during training, demonstrating generalization.
To visualize the model's prediction behavior across the full yield range, Fig. 20 presents the relationship between predicted and actual yields for both training and test sets.
Points cluster more tightly in the mid-yield range (5,000-13,000 kg) where Phase 1 observations concentrated (median 6,287 kg, IQR 4,410-10,434 kg), with greater dispersion at extremes reflecting sparse training data (<4,000 kg and >15,000 kg). Test samples distribute along the diagonal similarly to training samples, confirming generalization rather than memorization. While Fig. 20 shows overall prediction alignment with actual yields, residual analysis provides deeper insight into error patterns and potential systematic bias. Fig. 21 presents residuals (actual minus predicted yield) for both datasets.
Residuals scatter randomly around zero without systematic patterns (funnel shapes, curves), with most within ±3,000 kg. This validates suggesting that the 27 features derived from Phase 1 explorations (activity-based organization: pre-planting, nutrient management, pest management, environmental challenges) captured many of the key yield drivers. The balanced distribution above and below zero confirms absence of systematic over- or under-prediction.
Outlier residuals (>±4,000 "kg" ) correspond to extreme yields (Table 9: minimum 1,220 kg, maximum 20,790 kg). For example, the test sample with the largest negative residual (-6,700 kg) had actual yield 20,790 kg (the maximum), which the model conservatively predicted at ~14,000 kg due to sparse training examples above 15,000 kg.
The validated Random Forest model (200 trees, max_depth=10, sqrt feature selection) achieving R^2=0.765 on the test set established the prediction performance baseline for the Python scikit-learn implementation. To enable offline yield prediction on Android devices (FR1), the model required conversion from Python to Java code via m2cgen. The following section presents the model export process and numerical parity validation to ensure the Java implementation preserved prediction accuracy.
 
Fig. 21. Residual plot for training (blue) and test (orange) sets. Vertical lines show error magnitudes relative to zero. Random scatter indicates no systematic bias.
Model export and parity validation
Following validation of the Random Forest model's predictive performance on the held-out test set, the model was exported from Python scikit-learn to Java code using m2cgen (Model to Code Generator, version 0.10.0) to enable offline prediction on Android devices without requiring internet connectivity (FR1) or server infrastructure.
The m2cgen library transpiled the trained Random Forest Regressor (200 trees, 27 input features, max_depth=10) into a standalone Java class containing a score(double[] features) method that implements the complete decision logic of all 200 trees without external dependencies. The exported code consists of nested if-else statements representing the decision tree structure, with feature thresholds and leaf values hardcoded from the trained model, enabling deterministic predictions identical to the original Python implementation.
To ensure conversion fidelity, numerical parity validation compared predictions between the original Python scikit-learn model and the exported Java implementation across all test set samples (n=17). The parity testing methodology, detailed in Appendix 8, involved extracting the 27 feature values for each test sample, executing both Python and Java predictions, and computing absolute differences and relative errors. A tolerance threshold of 0.01% was established as the acceptance criterion, consistent with industry standards for model deployment validation. 
Table 15 presents the parity validation results summarizing the comparison across all 17 test samples. For this test set, numerical parity was achieved, with observed absolute differences of 0.00 kg and relative errors of 0.0000% for every prediction (to the recorded precision). These results indicate that, for the evaluated samples, the Java implementation replicated the Python model’s outputs exactly, with no detectable rounding errors or implementation discrepancies within the chosen precision. The zero-difference outcome is well within the 0.01% tolerance threshold, supporting the conclusion that m2cgen’s code generation preserved the trained tree structure, feature thresholds, and leaf values for this model configuration.
This validation addressed the computational constraint, where m2cgen code generation file size limits necessitated restricting the model to ≤200 trees and max_depth ≤10. The successful parity validation confirmed that these constraints did not compromise prediction accuracy during conversion, and that the selected configuration (200 trees, depth 10) remained within m2cgen's operational limits while preserving the test set performance metrics documented in Table 14.
The validated Java model established the foundation for integration into the Android application architecture, where it operates completely offline without external libraries or network connectivity. The model receives farmer-provided feature values and generates yield predictions directly on the mobile device, eliminating the need for server infrastructure and enabling real-time decision support in areas with limited internet access.
Table 15. Numerical parity validation comparing Python scikit-learn and Java m2cgen predictions on test set (n=17 farms).
Statistic	Absolute Difference (kg)	Relative Error (%)
Mean	0.00	0.0000
Standard Deviation	0.00	0.0000
Maximum	0.00	0.0000
Minimum	0.00	0.0000
Samples passing tolerance (<0.01%)	17/17 (100%)	

Mobile Application Development
Following the derivation of functional and non-functional requirements from empirical farmer observations (Table 10-Table 11) and the validation of the Random Forest prediction model with numerical parity between the Python and Java implementations (Table 15), the construction phase produced a working Android prototype of the GabayPalay mobile application. The application was implemented in Android Studio using Kotlin, with the m2cgen-generated Java Random Forest model embedded directly in the application package so that yield predictions operate entirely offline without internet connectivity. This design responded directly to the offline operation and device constraint requirements specified earlier (FR1, NFR1).
This section describes how farmers use GabayPalay in practice and highlights the main functionalities of the application. These include guiding users through staged data entry that mirrors rice production activities, automatically converting fertilizer products into NPK nutrient values, recording pest and weather conditions, generating yield predictions with transparent explanations, and maintaining a history of past predictions that farmers can review, compare, and relate to actual yields. The system context and high-level control flow are presented in this chapter, while detailed architecture, data flow, and control-flow diagrams are provided in Appendix 11.
From a system perspective, GabayPalay operates as a closed, offline tool in which the farmer is the sole external entity providing inputs and receiving outputs. The system context is shown in Fig. 22. In this context diagram, the farmer supplies information on land characteristics, variety choice, seed quantity, fertilizer applications, pest management practices, and weather-related challenges. GabayPalay processes these inputs entirely on the device and returns yield predictions, explanatory information, and basic recommendations. No external servers, online databases, or third-party services are involved in this process, which reflects the offline-first architecture and local-only data handling required by connectivity and privacy constraints.
Internally, the application organizes its operations into a small number of logical processes that mirror the main farming activities documented in Phase 1. As summarized in Fig. 23, GabayPalay collects data through four input modules, pre-planting preparation, fertilizer management, pest management, and environmental challenges, before aggregating these inputs for yield prediction and historical storage. The pre-planting module (Process 1.0) gathers basic farm and establishment characteristics. The fertilizer management module (Process 2.0) captures the number and type of fertilizer splits and converts commercial formulations into standardized NPK quantities. The pest management module (Process 3.0) records the presence of key pest and disease categories and associated protection inputs. The environmental challenges module (Process 4.0) records farmer-reported weather-related impacts. These data are then combined in the palay yield prediction module (Process 5.0), which invokes the embedded Random Forest model, and finally passed to the yield prediction history module (Process 6.0) for local storage and later retrieval. 
 
Fig. 22. Data flow diagram (DFD Level 0) showing the GabayPalay system context with the Farmer as the sole external entity interacting with the application through farm input data and receiving yield predictions and recommendations.
 
Fig. 23. Data flow diagram (DFD Level 1) showing the six major functional modules of the GabayPalay application and their interactions with the Farmer and Local Storage.
User interaction with GabayPalay follows a control flow that aligns with these internal processes. The main navigation structure is illustrated in Fig. 24. From the home screen, the user may initiate a new yield prediction or access the history of past predictions. These two pathways correspond to the core use cases identified in the requirements analysis, namely conducting a prediction session based on current management plans (FR1–FR5) and reviewing or comparing past scenarios over time (FR6). The more detailed control flows for each stage of the prediction and history workflows are presented in Appendix 11, while the subsections that follow focus on the user experience as shown in the user interface screenshots.
 
Fig. 24. Main navigation control flow showing entry points for the prediction workflow and history workflow.
When a user launches GabayPalay, a splash screen briefly displays the application branding, after which the home screen appears (Fig. 25a-b). The home screen provides two primary actions: starting a new prediction session and viewing previously saved predictions. For first-time users, an optional onboarding guide is presented (Fig. 25c). This guide introduces the staged input workflow, covering pre-planting information, fertilizer management, pest and disease management, and weather challenges, before leading to the results view. The onboarding screen includes a “Don’t show again” checkbox that allows more experienced users to bypass the guide on subsequent launches. 
 
(a)	 
(b)	 
(c)
Fig. 25. Application entry screens. (a) Splash screen displaying application branding during initialization; (b) Home screen with primary navigation options for prediction and history access; (c) Optional onboarding guide introducing the staged input workflow with option to skip on future launches.
This introductory flow directly addresses the digital literacy constraints observed in Phase 1, where all interviewed farmers reported no prior use of agricultural mobile applications (Table 6, Theme I12), by orienting them to the stepwise process before they encounter the detailed input forms. Taken together, the home screen and onboarding comprise the basic navigation and guidance functionality of GabayPalay.
After choosing to predict palay yield from the home screen, the user is taken to the pre-planting input interface (Fig. 26a). In this stage, the farmer enters basic farm characteristics that form the foundation of the prediction. These include land area in hectares, entered into a numeric input field; rice variety, chosen from a dropdown list distinguishing Hybrid and Inbred types; seed amount, entered in kilograms with an automatic conversion to sacks displayed to better match on-farm units; planting method, indicated through a dropdown menu, for example transplanted; and land preparation methods, selected via checkboxes for manual preparation, tractor use, and rotavator use. If any required field is left blank or contains invalid data, the interface displays contextual validation messages and highlights the problematic fields (Fig. 26b). The form cannot be submitted until all mandatory entries are valid. This stage implements the functionality for structured capture and validation of pre-planting information, which corresponds to the pre-planting and establishment features of the prediction model.
 
(a)	 
(b)
Fig. 26. Pre-planting input interface (FR3). (a) Data entry form displaying fields for land area, rice variety dropdown, seed amount, planting method dropdown, and land preparation checkboxes; (b) Input validation error feedback highlighting incomplete required field with contextual error message.
Upon successful completion of the pre-planting stage, the application guides the user to the nutrient management interface (Fig. 27). This screen was designed to reflect the three-stage fertilization pattern documented in both qualitative and quantitative findings (Table 7; Table 9), where farmers typically apply fertilizers at basal, mid-season, and late-season stages. The farmer first specifies the number of fertilizer applications, generally two or three, corresponding to these timings. For each application, the user selects a fertilizer formulation from a dropdown menu that includes Complete 14-14-14, Urea 46-0-0, Ammosul 21-0-0, Muriate of Potash 0-0-60, and Complete 16-20-0 (Fig. 27b-c). The farmer then enters the quantity applied and selects the measurement unit, either kilograms or 50‑kilogram sacks, matching the measurement habits noted during requirements planning (Fig. 27d-e). As these values are entered, GabayPalay automatically converts the reported fertilizer products and quantities into total nitrogen, phosphorus (as P₂O₅), and potassium (as K₂O) per application. These calculated nutrient amounts are displayed on the screen, allowing the farmer to see the implied NPK contributions of each split. This stage implements a key functionality of the app, namely automatic NPK calculation and stage-based fertilizer input management, which reduces the cognitive burden associated with fertilizer chemistry and directly supports the nutrient management features of the yield prediction model. 
Following nutrient management, the workflow proceeds to the pest and disease management stage, which is implemented through the pest management interface (Fig. 28). In this screen, the farmer indicates whether any of the five key pest and disease categories identified in Phase 1 are present: stem borer, rats, golden apple snail or kuhol, cutworms, and rice blast. 
 
(a)	 
(b)	 
(c)
 
(d)	 
(e)	
Fig. 27. Nutrient management interface for Stage-Based Input (FR2): (a) Selecting 2 or 3 application splits; (b) Fertilizer product dropdown; (c) Input fields for selected splits; (d) Kilogram unit selection; (e) Sack unit selection with 50kg conversion.
These categories are represented as checkboxes, enabling users to mark which threats have been observed or are expected in the current cropping season (Fig. 28a). When pests are selected, corresponding input fields appear for the farmer to record the quantities of insecticide, herbicide, rat poison, or molluscicide applied (Fig. 28b). In this way, the application captures both pest incidence and the associated protection inputs, reflecting the locally observed emphasis on preventive integrated pest management rather than routine calendar spraying (Table 6, Themes I2–I4; Table 9). This stage implements the functionality for pest and disease recording and for entering pesticide and related protection inputs that feed directly into the pest-related features of the model.
 
(a)	 
(b)
Fig. 28. Pest management interface (FR4). (a) Blank form showing checkboxes for common pests. (b) Completed form with selected pests and protection product quantities.
The subsequent screen focuses on weather-related challenges (Fig. 29). Instead of requiring detailed meteorological data, which are not consistently available at the farm level, GabayPalay uses a simple binary indicator to capture whether the crop experienced serious adverse weather. The farmer marks a single checkbox if the season was notably affected by flooding near transplanting, dry-season water shortages, strong typhoons, or related events, in line with the constraints on data availability discussed earlier (Table 8; Table 9). This simple input corresponds to the weather challenge feature used in the prediction model and preserves the ability to represent environmental stress without increasing the complexity of data entry. This stage implements the functionality for recording major weather-related constraints in a farmer-friendly way.
 
Fig. 29. Weather conditions input screen implementing the binary weather challenge indicator identified during requirements planning.
Beyond serving as a single binary input, the environmental challenge variable (X_27) supports several decision-oriented use cases in GabayPalay. First, for scenario-based risk assessment, farmers can generate comparative predictions under favorable weather conditions (X_27=0) and under challenging weather conditions (X_27=1) to understand how vulnerable a given management plan is to weather-related risks. This bracketing approach provides an expected yield range rather than a single point estimate. Second, for probability-based seasonal prediction, farmers can set X_27 according to typical local patterns. Because 80% of surveyed farms reported weather challenges during the reference period, a conservative prediction for a typical season would set X_27=1, whereas X_27=0 would be appropriate only when explicitly favorable seasonal forecasts. Third, for post-harvest yield gap analysis, farmers can enter the weather conditions they experienced to examine how adverse events interacted with their management practices. By revisiting saved predictions in the history module and using the feature importance visualization, they can identify which management factors contributed most to deviations between target and realized yields. In the user interface, the weather screen therefore guides farmers with the instruction: “Select YES if flooding or drought is expected based on seasonal forecasts; select NO only if weather conditions are forecasted to be favorable.” This framing acknowledges the probabilistic nature of weather while maintaining the variable’s practical utility for decision support.
Before a yield prediction is generated, the application presents an integrated review screen summarizing all previously entered information (Fig. 30a). This screen groups input according to the staged workflow, namely pre-planting characteristics, fertilizer applications and derived NPK totals, pest and disease indicators with associated control inputs, and the weather challenge indicator. The farmer can scroll through this consolidated view to verify the correctness of all entries. If discrepancies or mistakes are identified, the user can navigate back to the relevant stage, correct the values, and then return to the review screen. This stage implements review and correction functionality that allows users to check their data holistically before prediction, supporting more reliable use of the tool.
Once the farmer confirms the inputs, GabayPalay constructs the 27‑element feature vector internally and invokes the embedded Random Forest model. The prediction process completes within a few seconds during manual testing, and the user is then shown the result interface (Fig. 30b-c). The simple results view displays the predicted palay yield in kilograms, together with a conversion into sacks or using a 50‑kilogram assumption. Presenting the output in both scientific and farmer-familiar units helps bridge the gap between modelling outputs and everyday decision-making. A confidence indicator is also displayed, based on the model’s performance on the hold-out test set, reminding users that the prediction is an estimate supported by, but not guaranteed by, empirical data. The prediction is intended to inform planning rather than replace farmer judgement, by giving an estimate of likely yield under the current combination of inputs that the farmer can weigh against other possible management choices. This portion of the interface implements the core prediction functionality of GabayPalay and provides basic interpretive support through unit conversion and confidence indication.
For farmers who wish to examine the prediction in more detail, GabayPalay provides an expanded results view. In this screen (Fig. 30c), the predicted yield is accompanied by a visual prediction range, typically ±15% around the point estimate, which is rendered as a bar with lower and upper bounds. 
 
(a)	 
(c)	 
(d)
 
(b)		
Fig. 30. Input review and prediction interfaces for FR5 (Transparent Results). (a) Review modal summarizing categorized farm inputs before prediction; (b) Simple results display with predicted yield, unit conversions, and confidence; (c) Detailed results view with prediction range, insights, and recommendations; (d) Feature importance visualization showing relative influence of 27 inputs, generated via dynamic sensitivity analysis.
This representation allows farmers to mentally bracket plausible outcomes under similar conditions rather than interpreting the predicted value as a precise single number. Below the range visualization, the application displays concise insights and recommendations based on the pattern of inputs, using Material Design Chip components to highlight, for example, when fertilizer rates appear unusually low or high relative to the sample or when certain pests are present without corresponding protection inputs. Together, these elements implement an extended interpretive functionality that supports farmers in making sense of the prediction and in identifying potential adjustments to their management.
To support transparency and learning, GabayPalay also includes a feature importance visualization (Fig. 30d). For each prediction, the system perturbs individual inputs slightly and observes how the predicted yield changes. These marginal effects are then ranked and displayed as a horizontal bar chart, showing which inputs most strongly influenced the specific prediction. This personalized explanation helps users understand which aspects of their management, such as nitrogen rate, seed quantity, or variety choice, are driving the estimated outcome. This implements a model explanation functionality that addresses concerns about black-box behavior and supports more reflective decision-making, in line with Requirement FR5.
After viewing the prediction, the user can choose to save it. Saved predictions are stored locally on the device, and they can be accessed at any time through the history option on the home screen. The history interface (Fig. 31a-c) presents a list of past predictions in reverse chronological order, each entry showing the date and time of the prediction, the corresponding yield estimate in kilograms, and an indicator of whether the record has been 
 
(a)	 
(b)	 
(c)
Fig. 31. Prediction history interface for Requirement FR6: (a) History list showing the recent saved entry with timestamp, yield, and favorite toggle; (b) List displaying all predictions (reverse chronological); (c) Favorites view filtering bookmarked scenarios.
marked as a favorite. Farmers can switch between a view showing all predictions and a filtered view showing only favorites. By tapping on any history item, they can open a detailed view that presents both the original inputs and the previously generated prediction without recalculating. In this way, GabayPalay allows farmers to review and compare scenarios across seasons, supporting the longitudinal and experience-based decision-making patterns that were documented in the qualitative phase.
Beyond simple retrieval, this history functionality provides a central form of decision support in GabayPalay. Farmers can return to a saved prediction after harvest and mentally compare the model’s estimated yield with the actual yield obtained for that season. By inspecting the recorded inputs in the detailed view together with the weather conditions they experienced, they can reflect on which differences in management or environment might explain any gap between predicted and realized yields. In addition, by saving multiple prediction records for different planned combinations of seed rate, fertilizer splits, or pest management strategies, farmers can compare several what-if scenarios before implementation and select the option that appears most appropriate given their resource constraints and risk preferences. In this way, GabayPalay does not only calculates a single yield value, but it also supports farmers in evaluating and comparing alternative management decisions over time.
Although GabayPalay was implemented around a 27-feature Random Forest model, the inputs are not used solely for numerical prediction. They also enable several forms of decision support from the farmer’s perspective. Before planting, farmers can adjust controllable inputs such as seed rate, fertilizer splits and product choices, variety, planting method, and pest management strategies, then generate and compare multiple predictions in the history module in order to explore “what-if” scenarios under different management plans. During the season, they can revisit stored predictions and use the feature importance visualization to see which specific inputs, for example nitrogen rate, seed quantity, or pest control measures, are driving the current yield estimate. After harvest, farmers can compare predicted yields with actual outcomes for the same recorded inputs and weather conditions, and reflect on which management factors were most strongly associated with yield gains or losses across seasons. In this way, the full input set functions both as a basis for machine learning prediction and as a structured representation of management decisions that GabayPalay uses to support planning, comparison, and post-hoc learning, rather than only as a calculator of a single yield value.
Pre-deployment manual testing on Android devices meeting the minimum specification (Android 8.0, API level 26) indicated that the full workflow, from initial launch, through staged input, to prediction and history review, could be completed offline without performance or stability issues under typical use. All data entry, prediction, and history retrieval operate without network permission, and all information is stored in the application’s private storage area. This behavior meets the core constraints on connectivity and privacy that emerged in Phase 1 (NFR1, NFR4), and initial testing also indicated that prediction responses were within the targeted performance range and that input validation and error handling prevented obvious failures (NFR3, NFR5). More detailed evaluation of usability, perceived usefulness, and ease of use, including System Usability Scale and Technology Acceptance Model assessments, is presented in the subsequent chapter.
User Acceptance Testing and Usability Evaluation
Following implementation and internal validation of the GabayPalay application, user acceptance testing was conducted with rice farmers from Hagonoy, Davao del Sur to evaluate usability, perceived usefulness, and adoption potential. This section presents the results of RAD Phase 5 (Cutover and Validation), including participant characteristics, quantitative usability assessment using the System Usability Scale (SUS), technology acceptance evaluation using the Technology Acceptance Model (TAM), qualitative user feedback, and task completion analysis that are briefly described in Appendix 10. In contrast to the internal non-functional validation reported in the previous section, which focused on connectivity, performance, and data handling, the user evaluation presented here provides empirical evidence for the usability and accessibility requirement NFR2.
User acceptance testing involved 36 rice farmers from Hagonoy, Davao del Sur. Participants were identified with the help of associations and cooperatives, following the sampling procedures described in the methodology. Participants were drawn from the same locality as the Phase 1 interview (n = 11) and survey (n = 54) respondents, ensuring consistency in farming practices, environmental conditions, and technology access patterns that informed the requirements specification. 
The sample was predominantly male (83.3%), reflecting typical gender roles in farm management in Philippine rice systems. Ages ranged from early twenties to late fifties, with balanced representation across age cohorts. Educational attainment was mainly elementary and high school level (80.5% combined), similar to the Phase 1 survey profile, and consistent with the digital literacy constraints that motivated simplified interaction patterns under NFR2. 
Daily smartphone usage was concentrated in the 1–3-hour range (38.9%), with over one-quarter of participants using smartphones less than 1 hour per day. This distribution indicates moderate but not intensive digital engagement and underscores the need for interfaces that remain usable for users with limited technology exposure. Prior agricultural app use was rare; 86.1% reported never having used any agricultural mobile application, while a small subset had experience with tools such as Rice Doctor, Rice Crop Manager, PlantNet, RiceAdvice, and postharvest quality tools. Farming experience ranged from 2 to 35 years (median 18 years), and farm sizes were characteristic of smallholder systems, with most participants managing 1–3 hectares. Overall, the UAT sample reflects the diversity and constraints of the intended user population. Table 17 summarizes the demographic characteristics of the UAT participants.
