The System Usability Scale (SUS) was used to quantify perceived usability. The instrument consists of ten items rated on a five-point Likert scale, converted to a composite score from 0 to 100 following Brooke's (1996) standard procedure. To understand how farmers evaluated specific aspects of GabayPalay before deriving the overall SUS score, item-level responses were first examined. Table 17 presents the mean scores for each of the ten SUS items. 
Table 17. Item-level System Usability Scale (SUS) scores for GabayPalay (n = 36).
Individual SUS Items*	Mean Score	Interpretation
SUS1	3.53	Moderate positive intention
SUS2	2.81	Moderate complexity perception
SUS3	3.75	Moderate to high ease of use perception
SUS4	3.19	Moderate support dependency
SUS5	3.58	Good integration perception
SUS6	2.50	Low inconsistency perception
SUS7	3.58	Moderate learnability perception
SUS8	2.50	Low awkwardness perception
SUS9	3.78	Moderate to high confidence
SUS10	3.11	Moderate learning barrier
* Complete SUS item statements are included in Appendix 6.
Item-level means indicate generally positive responses to statements about ease of use, integration, and confidence (SUS3, SUS5, SUS7, SUS9), but also reveal concerns about needing technical support and the learning effort required (SUS4, SUS10). The relatively low scores for perceived inconsistency and cumbersomeness (SUS6, SUS8) suggest that the interface is structurally coherent, and that complexity arises more from content and task demands than from inconsistent layout.
Based on these item-level patterns, composite SUS scores were then computed to provide an overall measure of usability. Summary statistics for the SUS scores of the 36 farmer participants are presented in Table 18. The mean SUS score of 60.3 (SD = 19.5) is below the commonly cited benchmark of approximately 68 for clearly acceptable usability and below the target specified in NFR2. Using the interpretive ranges suggested by Bangor et al. (2009), this value corresponds to marginal to acceptable usability. The wide range (27.5 to 100.0) and high standard deviation indicate substantial variability in user experience. In this sample, 41.7% of participants rated the system at or above 70, and 16.7% rated it at or above 80, while others assigned much lower scores. 
Table 18. Summary statistics for System Usability Scale scores (n = 36).
Overall SUS Score	Value	Interpretation
Mean SUS Score	60.3	Below acceptable threshold (Brooke, 1996; Bangor et al., 2009)
Standard Deviation	19.5	High variability across users
Minimum Score	27.5	Lowest individual rating
Maximum Score	100.0	Highest individual rating (perfect score)
Median Score	58.8	Central tendency indicator
Scores ≥70 (Acceptable)	15 (41.7%)	Proportion meeting acceptability threshold
Scores ≥80 (Excellent)	6 (16.7%)	Proportion rating as excellent

Younger farmers, those with higher educational attainment, and those with more intensive smartphone use tended to assign higher SUS scores and to complete the workflow with fewer difficulties, whereas elementary-educated farmers with less than one hour of daily smartphone usage often provided low SUS ratings and required more guidance. These findings align with the digital literacy and adoption constraints identified in the requirements phase and confirm that the interface is usable for a portion of the target population but challenging for users at the lower end of the digital literacy spectrum (Angchay et al., 2024; Gabrillo and Torres, 2022). 
To quantify the influence of education and digital experience on usability more precisely, SUS scores were also stratified by educational attainment and daily smartphone usage (Table 19). The results show a clear gradient. Farmers with only elementary education (n = 12) reported a mean SUS of 38.54 (SD = 8.01), while those with high school education (n = 17) reported a substantially higher mean of 68.68 (SD = 9.69), and those with college level or graduate education (n = 7) reported a mean SUS of 77.14 (SD = 19.33). A similar pattern appears for daily smartphone usage. Participants using smartphones less than one hour per day (n = 10) had a mean SUS of 37.00 (SD = 7.89), compared with 61.79 (SD = 9.97) among those using smartphones 1–3 hours (n = 14), 75.36 (SD = 11.94) among those using smartphones 3–5 hours (n = 7), and 81.50 (SD = 18.08) among those using smartphones more than five hours per day (n = 5). In other words, GabayPalay approaches or exceeds the commonly cited SUS benchmark of 70 for farmers with at least high school education and moderate to high smartphone usage but falls well below this threshold for farmers with elementary education and very limited smartphone exposure.
These stratified results quantitatively support the qualitative observations that the current interface is much more usable for more educated and digitally experienced farmers than for those with lower education and minimal smartphone use. Taken together, the SUS results and subgroup stratification indicate that GabayPalay has achieved moderate but not yet optimal usability. The system satisfies NFR2 only partially: it reaches acceptable usability levels for a subset of the target population, but additional refinements are needed to make the interface consistently usable across the broader population of smallholder farmers in Hagonoy.
Table 19. SUS scores stratified by educational attainment and daily smartphone.
Characteristic	n	Mean SUS	SD
Education Level			
Elementary	12	38.54	8.01
High School Graduate	17	68.68	9.69
College Level/Graduate	7	77.14	19.33
